I often think that Millennials may be the last generation capable of purely appreciating art and forming genuine connections with artists. They don't have that pressure to view everything through a critical, biased lens.
We grew up during the golden age of media, when people shared a common understanding of pop culture, but now that collective awareness has disappeared.
At that time, we could immerse ourselves directly in the content without considering its source, because in that era, tracing back origins was not easy.
We worshipped these artists without any reason to question that reverence. Thus, we formed a "pseudo-social relationship" with them, which we regarded as an essential part of life.
This also explains why we are so obsessed with nostalgia.
When The Office was still on air, my friends and I would gather every Thursday to watch the show together, eating pizza along the way.
This is completely different from our current experience of watching shows through streaming platforms. Streaming services usually release all 12 episodes at once, and everyone watches at their own pace. When posting about the plot on social media, we often add “spoiler warning,” or simply discuss in specific groups.
Subconsciously, we all long for that sense of collective belonging that connected everyone.
It's also precisely because of this nostalgia that we keep rewatching shows like The Office or movies like Broadcast News, where those unforgettable classic lines circulate online like memes.
We quote these classic lines from the works and assume most people understand what we're referring to.
Nowadays, even if something goes viral online, we can't assume that everyone has seen it.
With the information explosion, there's just too much to pay attention to, and we can't really filter it all… Are we ever going to be able to escape this information overload?
We keep discovering new media and new artists, only to find out that they're either sexual predators or stubborn individuals full of prejudice—this cycle is exhausting.
We are caught between a desire for nostalgia and the realization that the people who created the art we love might have serious moral flaws, and this conflicting mindset leaves us feeling lost.
We will be more careful in forming "pseudo-social relationships" with artists.
We gradually realized that if someone wants to gain wealth and power, it's hard to guarantee they won't hurt or exploit others.
Since collective media awareness has disappeared, we have developed a class consciousness that helps us maintain critical thinking.
Of course, there are still some people who are stubborn and insist on placing others on a pedestal, only to pretend to be shocked when their idols fall.
We are in an era of transformation, and I urgently want to know where we are heading.
